,
    abstract = { Abstract.This paper considers a problem of testing, from a finite sample, a topological conjugacy of two trajectories coming from dynamical systems \((X,f)\) and \((Y,g)\). More precisely, given \(x\_1,\ldots, x\_n \subset X\) and \(y\_1,\ldots, y\_n \subset Y\) such that \(x\_{i+1} = f(x\_i)\) and \(y\_{i+1} = g(y\_i)\) as well as \(h: X \rightarrow Y\), we deliver a number of tests to check if \(f\) and \(g\) are topologically conjugated via \(h\). The values of the tests are close to zero for systems conjugate by \(h\) and large for systems that are not. Convergence of the test values, in the case when the sample size goes to infinity, is established. We provide a number of numerical examples indicating scalability and robustness of the presented methods. In addition, we show how the presented method gives rise to a test of sufficient embedding dimension, mentioned in Takens’ embedding theorem. Our methods also apply to the situation when we are given two observables of deterministic processes, of a form of one or higher dimensional time series. In this case, their similarity can be assessed by comparing the dynamics of their Takens’ reconstructions. Finally, we include a proof-of-concept study using the presented methods to search for an approximation of the homeomorphism conjugating given systems. }
}

